&lt;h2 id=&quot;how-to-win-at-aria-and-influence-web-accessibility-by-tolu-adegbite&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;How to Win at ARIA and Influence Web Accessibility by Tolu Adegbite&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The point of ARIA is to indicate to assistive technologies about whatâ€™s visually happening on a component.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Itâ€™s important for UX designers to understand how ARIA works, because itâ€™s how nonsighted users will experience the web. Otherwise you delegate that decision-making entirely to devs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Tolu recommends doubling up in code when using native HTML landmarks, since assistive tech reads them out inconsistently. So even if youâ€™re using &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;nav&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; itâ€™s a good idea to also use &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;role=â€œnavigationâ€&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; to make sure all your bases are covered!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Overdoing ARIA attributes can make the experience worse than not using ARIA at all. â€œA role is a promise.â€&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you donâ€™t understand how an ARIA attribute works, itâ€™s better not to use it. Always prioritize native HTML tags. Do not change native semantics unless you really have to. Make sure interactive ARIA controls are visible and usable with a keyboard.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Itâ€™s been a long time since Iâ€™ve had to implement ARIA attributes myself, but itâ€™s super cool that thereâ€™s ways to indicate context to nonsighted users, like â€œcomplementaryâ€ landmarks for related content!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The attribute &lt;code&gt;aria-describedby&lt;/code&gt; can be useful in a password text field to connect it to its help text, so the help text is read when they land on the password field instead of having to tab over. Thatâ€™s part of the userâ€™s experience!&lt;/p&gt;
