&lt;p&gt;Garbage in is garbage out. (For real. SF.govâ€™s COVID content makes sense because the public health guidance makes sense! I canâ€™t make ðŸ’© not-ðŸ’©!)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Tools beat rules. Rules are good and fine, but how are you helping people apply it to their writing? (Make it easy for people to do the right thing, and hard to do the wrong thing!)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Jargon is jargon! (Including â€œplain language.â€ Explain what you mean!)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A tip for training writing to subject matter experts: Even Einstein had to learn to tie his shoes! As a power user, you may be using tools that not everyone knows about. Share tips that people might find helpful, even maybe (gasp!) fun!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Tours are not the same as training! Just showing people where stuff is not nearly enough. Look as far ahead as you need to, book some actual trainings for people.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To help people start writing, Scott reminds us that â€œstealing is natural.â€ Even for yourselfâ€”helps in the preparation step! Although itâ€™s yet another fear we have to unlearn from school! Most writing for government, business, UX, etc, donâ€™t need to be original.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Fidelity is freeing. Make it clear if someone is working with â€œlow fidelityâ€ text (i.e. first drafts) and incorporate the culture that writing takes work. Can use colors or fonts (yup, Comic Sans!).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Remind people that â€œgood writing works.â€ Avoid an unbalanced focus on grammar perfection. Get it out and helping people ASAP!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Crits are critical. Talk about content goals, then workshop it together. Thatâ€™s a massive training and educational opportunity! Scott says he leaves 1 hour per week for content crits. (I admittedly donâ€™t do this enough because COVID content is ASAP! ðŸ™)&lt;/p&gt;
