&lt;p&gt;Enterprise doesnâ€™t have the luxury of using a scorched earth strategy when dealing with legacy tech.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Think of the long game. Build relationships with your stakeholders. Build a design roadmap to keep yourself on track as you compromise in the current product.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Compromise shitty legacy tech with unicorn design. Make a unicorn out of trash, aka a â€œtrashicorn.â€&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&quot;test-with-your-customers&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Test with your customers&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Use data-informed design. Data analytics is helpful, but wonâ€™t tell you the why.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;How to find users to test with:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Recruit the sales team (could also help with how much to pay them too)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Hit up LinkedIn groups&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use market research agencies&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Go guerilla! Hit up personal networks, cold-call.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ever feel so tired and stressed, you canâ€™t figure out how you ended up doing what youâ€™re doing? Between work and/or school, family, friends, errands of adult life, we are running from one thing to another, not having a second to stop and take a breather. We just canâ€™t afford the time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;â€œItâ€™s just the realities of adult life,â€ we tell ourselves. Adulthood means doing things we donâ€™t want to do.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We tell ourselves that life nowadays is better, because we have more choices. Expectations are not that strict as they were when it comes to careers, children, where to live, what to do for fun. We have freedom! But do we really?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I believe itâ€™s time to rethink adulthood, and bring back some lessons from childhood.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The truth is, todayâ€™s world has so many ways to compare our lives to others. There are lifestyle magazines, business blogs, reality shows, not to mention social media. We keep up with what everyone is doing, and we consciously or unconsciously want to keep up. Thereâ€™s an actual term for that now: FOMO, the fear of missing out.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We have endless possibilities to model ourselves after. But in doing so, we can lose sight of what we really want for ourselves.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Letâ€™s put the brakes on adulthood, and go back to that annoying little kid we all once were. That annoying little kid that always asked the same question. â€œWhy?â€&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But instead of annoying other people, letâ€™s annoy ourselves. Say, youâ€™re just really tired every Wednesday night, are a little frazzled having to write your speeches and practice them, and having a meeting after a full dayâ€™s work.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So you ask yourself, â€œWhy? Why am I here at Toastmasters today?â€&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And everyone will have a different answer. â€œThe people are nice.â€ â€œItâ€™s a nice break from work.â€ â€œI really need to practice my public speaking.â€ â€œI need to practice my listening skills.â€&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And then go you deeper. â€œWhy do I need to practice my public speaking?â€ â€œIâ€™ll need to make more presentations at work.â€ â€œWhy do I care how my work presentations go?â€ â€œI want a promotion, or I want to earn more money, or I want to look good in front of my boss.â€ Or whatever it is!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Keep asking why until you have an answer that either motivates you further, or maybe have you decide itâ€™s actually not that important to you. Then you can decide whether to take it off your long list of responsibilities. We donâ€™t need yet another thing! This will make our lives less busy, and more meaningful. We will be doing what we want to do, or at least be on the right path.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Weâ€™ll have different answers, which is the point. Weâ€™re all different. What works for other people, may not work for us.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So when you notice that youâ€™ve been unhappy for a while, take a breather. Be that annoying little kid again, and ask yourself why.&lt;/p&gt;
